0 FINGER~
Usage: finger <character name>

This command shows information about a character, like his/her real name,
email address, home page address and a message. In addition, if you have
the privilege to do so, you will be shown the last time that this character
was logged into Xania. This is mostly useful to immortals and to clan
leaders to track whether players have been logged in or not.

The information shown is set by using the setinfo command. Please see
help on setinfo for more information.
~

0 DAMAGE~
When one character attacks another, the severity of the damage is shown in the
verb used in the damage message.  The description of wounds can vary
wildly depending on the way you are attacking your opponent, for example 
using a fire spell will probably yield different results to using a
dagger.

If you are using an ANSI colour terminal (help colour) the colour of
the description will to some extent, indicate the level of damage. A
moderate level of damage will be in |Ggreen|w, a high level of damage
will be in |Yyellow|w, a fatal blow is likely to be |Wwhite|w or |Rred|w!
~



0 DEATH~
  -- "The reaper holds the hourglass with your name on it"

When your character dies, you are reincarnated back at the Altar of
the Temple of Isca.  Your corpse is left behind in the room where you
were killed, together with all of your equipment.  Your gold stays
with you as Death doesn't care much for money.

Any spells which were affecting you are canceled by Death.

Following and groups are not affected by Death.

You lose experience points for dying:

|WIf you are below level 25:|w
The amount you lose is half-way back to the beginning of your level.  Thus if 
you have a bad day and die several times,  the penalties won't clobber you.

|WIf you are level 25 and above:|w
The amount you lose is half of your experience to level.  This means you can
and will lose levels if you die with less than half a level's worth of
experience!!

Corpses decay after time, and the objects inside corpses decay with them.
Player corpses last *roughly* 30 hours of game time (15 minutes of real time).
Only the player who died, or someone in the same group, can retrieve objects
from a player's corpse. If the victim type 'noloot' his corpse can be
looted but it is recommended that you only do this if someone urgenty
needs to remove the contents from your corpse.

~




92 IMMCHALLENGE~
Challenge is a mild form of PKILL; think of it as player duelling rather than
player killing. It permits players to fight in the combat arena. In order for
the fight to go ahead, an immortal of level 95+ must be available to supervise
and the players must be over level 20.

If a player challenges another, you will be prompted on the immortal channel.
It is the choice of a level 95+ immortal whether they undertake supervision
or not. Your |Woptions|w will be given to you when a challenge is made. Only
permit the challenge to go ahead if the circumstances are fair and the
intentions of the duellists genuine, i.e. don't permit it if someone
is challenging merely to irritate or intimidate someone.

When the challenge has been accepted by both players, you will type |cready|w.
The players will then be prompted to type ready too and this will trigger the
players to be automatically |Wtransferred|w to the preparation room. Restore
the duellists and let them spell up there and then. It is your discretion
whether you restore them for a second time or not.

You can stop the duel at any time by typing 'cancel'. Advise the players to
recall before they type ready if they have a pet, this way they know exactly
where the pet will be after the duel.

It is up to you to make sure that use of challenge doesn't cause bad vibes
between players; something which PKILL can do quite easily. Both you and
the players should maintain good MUD etiquette, e.g. if one disarms the other
and takes the weapon during the duel, he should return it after! As the
controlling Imm, you are responsible for the smooth running of any duels.

Duelling might be included as part of a quest but remember that for events
such as this, a certain level of fairness must be maintained i.e. don't have
players who are 20 levels apart fighting each other.
See also: |Whelp challenge|w, |Chelp duel|w and |Phelp pkill|w
~

0 CHALLENGE~
Syntax: challenge <character>
        on line help is given when you are challenged

The challenge command may be used to initiate a duel between you and another
player, given that you are above level 20. If you are challenged yourself,
you will be presented with the basic details of the challenger and you will
have a time limit within which you will be able to |Waccept|w the challenge.

You will be given guidance about turning down, accepting and preparing for
a duel by the immortals of Xania when you are challenged.

|WDuels can be viewed|w by other players if they go to the Midgaard viewing
gallery which overlooks the Combat arena.

See also: |Whelp pkill|w and |Chelp duel|w
~

0 PKILL 'PLAYER KILL'~

Although |Wchallenge|w is a form of |Wplayer killing|w it is not as extreme
as seen on other MUDS. Challenge is a way of testing your combat prowess
against another player and if you lose, |Ryou will not be penalised in terms
of your experience or levels|w and you will lose none of your equipment.
For this reason, think of challenge as player kill refined into player
duelling.

Please don't abuse this feature by, for example, being spiteful towards
a player you may have killed. |WPKILL|w on some MUDS tends to make them very
nasty places, and on Xania the Immortals do not wish such unpleasantness to
exist.

See also: |Whelp duel|w and |Chelp challenge|w
~

0 DUEL~
Syntax: duel <character>

You will use this after you have prepared (i.e. 'spelled up') in the
preparation room. It will start a fight to the death. You will lose a duel
if you flee or if you are killed. If you are killed, you will be transferred
to the temple altar as if you had been killed under normal circumstances.
The victor can then walk safely out of the duelling pit.

See also: |Whelp pkill|w and |Chelp challenge|w
~


0 EXPERIENCE LEVEL XP~
Your character advances in power by gaining experience. You need a varying
amount of experience to gain per level, depending on what sort of character
you have. The more creation points you score during the creation of your
character, the more experience required to level, and the minimum is
40 creation points -> 1000 experience per level.

You gain experience by:

    being part of a group that kills a monster

You lose experience by:

    fleeing from combat
    recalling out of combat
    being the target of certain spells
    dying

The experience you get from a kill depends on several things: how many players
are in your group; your level versus the level of the monster; your alignment
versus the monster's alignment; how many of this monster have been killed
lately; and some random variation.
~

